 SR\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |1 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |1 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |1 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |1 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | '''4 / 9'''\n|}\n\n* R = tournament restricted to French nationals.\n\n<sup>*</sup>Through 1923, the French Championships were open only to French nationals. The World Hard Court Championships (WHCC), actually played on clay in Paris or Brussels, began in 1912 and were open to all nationalities. The results from that tournament are shown here from 1912 through 1914 and from 1920 through 1923. The Olympics replaced the WHCC in 1924, as the Olympics were held in Paris. Beginning in 1925, the French Championships were open to all nationalities, with the results shown here beginning with that year.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Tom Carter and Jim Hotchkiss, ''First Lady of Tennis: Hazel Hotchkiss Wightman'' (June, 2001), Creative Arts Book Company, {{ISBN|978-0887393341}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Tennis Hall of Fame}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* [http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1085969/2/index.htm 1972 Sports Illustrated Article \u2013 ''The Original Little Old Lady In Tennis Shoes'']\n\n{{navboxes|title=Hazel Hotchkiss Wightman in the [[grand slam (tennis)|Grand Slam Tournaments]]\n| list1=\n{{U.S. National Championships women's singles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon women's doubles champions}}\n{{U.S. National Championships women's doubles champions}}\n{{U.S. National Championships mixed doubles champions}}\n}}\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Tennis Women's Doubles}}\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Tennis Mixed Doubles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wightman, Hazel}}\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1974 deaths]]\n[[Category:American female tennis players]]\n[[Category:Olympic tennis players of the United States]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 1924 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medalists for the United States in tennis]]\n[[Category:United States National champions (tennis)]]\n[[Category:People from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:International Tennis Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Healdsburg, California]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in women's singles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in women's doubles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in mixed doubles]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1924 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American tennis and badminton player}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                              = Hazel Hotchkiss Wightman<br><small>[[Order of the British Empire|CBE]]</small>\n|image                             = Hazel hotchkiss 1910.jpg\n|caption                           = Wightman in 1910\n|fullname                          = Hazel Virginia Hotchkiss Wightman\n|itf_name                          = Hazel Wightman\n|country                           = {{USA}}\n|residence                         = \n|birth_date                        = {{birth date|1886|12|20}}\n|birth_place                       = [[Healdsburg]], California, U.S.\n|death_date                        = {{death date and age|1974|12|05|1886|12|20}}\n|death_place                       = [[Newton, Massachusetts|Newton]], Massachusetts, U.S.\n|height                            = \n|college                           = \n|turnedpro                         = \n|retired                           = \n|plays                             = Right-handed\n|careerprizemoney                  = \n|tennishofyear                     = 1957\n|tennishofid                       = hazel-hotchkiss-wightman\n|website                           = \n|singlesrecord                     = \n|singlestitles                     = \n|highestsinglesranking             = \n|AustralianOpenresult              = \n|FrenchOpenresult                  = \n|Wimbledonresult                   = 3R (1924)\n|USOpenresult                      = '''W''' ([[1909 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1909]], [[1910 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1910]], [[1911 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1911]], 1919)\n|Othertournaments                  = \n|MastersCupresult                  = \n|WTAChampionshipsresult            = \n|Olympicsresult                    = \n|doublesrecord                     = \n|doublestitles                     = \n|highestdoublesranking             = \n|grandslamsdoublesresults          =\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult       = \n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult           = \n|WimbledonDoublesresult            = '''W''' (1924)\n|USOpenDoublesresult               = '''W''' (1909, 1910, 1911, 1915, 1924, 1928)\n|OthertournamentsDoubles           = \n|MastersCupDoublesresult           = \n|WTAChampionshipsDoublesresult     = \n|OlympicsDoublesresult             = \n|Mixed                             = <!-- adds mixed information-->\n|mixedrecord                       = \n|mixedtitles                       = \n|AustralianOpenMixedresult         = \n|FrenchOpenMixedresult             = \n|WimbledonMixedresult              = \n|USOpenMixedresult                 = '''W''' (1909, 1910, 1911, 1915, 1918, 1920)\n|OthertournamentsMixedDoubles      = \n|OlympicMixedDoublesresult         = \n| medaltemplates-expand            = yes\n| medaltemplates                   =\n{{MedalCompetition|Olympic Games \u2013 [[Tennis at the Summer Olympics|Tennis]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1924 Summer Olympics|1924 Paris]]|[[Tennis at the 1924 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's doubles|Doubles]]}}\n{{MedalGold|1924 Paris|[[Tennis at the 1924 Summer Olympics \u2013 Mixed doubles|Mixed doubles]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Hazel Hotchkiss Wightman''', [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] (n\u00e9e Hotchkiss; December 20, 1886 \u2013 December 5, 1974) was an American [[tennis]] player and founder of the [[Wightman Cup]], an annual team competition for British and American women. She dominated American women's tennis before World War I, and won 45 U.S. titles during her life.\n\n==Personal life==\nWightman was born Hazel Virginia Hotchkiss in Healdsburg, California to William Joseph and Emma Lucretia (Grove) Hotchkiss. In February 1912, at the age of 25, she married George William Wightman of Boston. Her father-in-law, George Henry Wightman, was a leader in the steel industry, as an associate of [[Andrew Carnegie]], and one of the country's foremost pioneers of amateur tennis.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1937/04/21/94357643.html?pageNumber=23 |newspaper=New York Times |title=Geo. H. Wightman, Pioneer in Tennis|date=April 21, 1937}}</ref>\n\nShe became a member of Kappa Kappa Gamma at the University of California-Berkeley and served as the chapter's president.<ref>http://wiki.kappakappagamma.org/pages/Pi_Deuteron</ref>\n\nWightman was the mother of five children. She died at her home in the village of Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts on December 5, 1974.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1974/12/06/87613210.html?pageNumber=42|newspaper=New York Times |date=March 6, 1974 |author=Alfred E. Clark |title=Hazel Hotchkiss Wightman Dies; Holder of Tennis Titles was 86}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973, Queen Elizabeth II made her an honorary [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]].\n\n==Career highlights==\nWightman dominated American women's tennis before World War I and had an unparalleled reputation for sportsmanship. Wightman won a lifetime total of 45 U.S. titles, the last at age 68. She won 16 titles overall at the [[U.S. Open (tennis)|U.S. Championships]], four of them in singles (1909\u201311, 1919). Nine of her titles at the U.S. Championships came from 1909 to 1911, when she swept the singles, women's doubles, and mixed doubles competitions three consecutive years.<ref>{{cite book|last=Collins|first=Bud|title=The Bud Collins History of Tennis|year=2010|publisher=New Chapter Press|location=[New York]|isbn=978-0942257700|edition=2nd|pages=467, 468, 479, 481}}</ref>\n\nWightman is known as the \"Queen Mother of American Tennis\" or \"Lady Tennis\" for her lifelong participation in and promotion of women's tennis and because she was instrumental in organizing the Ladies International Tennis Challenge between British and American women's teams, better known as the [[Wightman Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hall of Famers \u2013 Hazel Hotchkiss Wightman|url=http://www.tennisfame.com/hall-of-famers/inductees/hazel-hotchkiss-wightman|publisher=International Tennis Hall of Fame|accessdate=22 September 2012}}</ref> The cup first was held in 1923 and continued through 1989. She played five years on the American team and was the captain of the American team from inception of the competition through 1948. The cup was composed of five singles and two doubles matches. The cup itself was donated in 1923 by Wightman in honor of her husband. The first contest at Forest Hills, New York on August 11 and 13, 1923 was won by the United States.\n\nBorn during the early days of American tennis, Wightman was a frail and awkward child. Her doctor recommended that she take up a sport to strengthen herself. Her brother suggested tennis as it was considered a \"genteel\" sport. Wightman learned to play at the nearby courts of the University of California, Berkeley where she graduated in 1911. Her rivalry with fellow Californian, [[May Sutton]], shaped a new women's game, with Wightman attacking the net to counter Sutton's dominating forehand.<ref name=ohnsorg>{{cite book|last=Ohnsorg|first=Roger W.|title=Robert Lindley Murray: The Reluctant U.S. Tennis Champion; includes \"The First Forty Years of American Tennis\"|publisher=Trafford On Demand Pub|location=Victoria, BC|isbn=978-1-4269-4514-4|page=47}}</ref>\n\nWightman devoted herself to teaching young people, opening her home near Boston's [[Longwood Cricket Club]] to aspiring champions. In recognition of Wightman's contributions to tennis, the [[United States Tennis Association#Awards|USTA Service Bowl]] was donated in her honor. In 1973, Wightman was appointed as an honorary Commander of the [[Commander of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|Order of the British Empire]].<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1913&dat=19730825&id=uqMgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=p2gFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1056,3618634&hl=en \"You would like to be served this time\"], Lewiston Evening journal, 25 August 1973</ref><ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/wi/hazel-wightman-1.html Olympic profile of Hazel Wightman], Sports-Reference.com</ref>\n\n*17 [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] titles (4 singles, 7 women's doubles, 6 mixed doubles)\n*Won all three titles at the U.S. Championships: 1909\u20131911\n*Won singles title at the U.S. Championships: 1909\u20131911, 1919\n*Runner-up in singles at the U.S. Championships: 1915\n*Won women's doubles title at the U.S. Championships: 1909\u20131911, 1915, 1924, 1928\n*Runner-up in women's doubles at the U.S. Championships: 1919, 1923\n*Won mixed doubles title at the U.S. Championships: 1909\u20131911, 1915, 1918, 1920\n*Runner-up in mixed doubles at the U.S. Championships: 1926\n*Won women's doubles title at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]: 1924\n*Olympic gold medalist in women's doubles and mixed doubles: 1924\n*Won singles title at the [[US Indoors|U.S. Indoor Championships]]: 1919, 1927\n*Won women's doubles title at the U.S. Indoor Championships: 1919, 1921, 1924, 1927\u20131931, 1933, 1943\n*Runner-up in women's doubles at the U.S. Indoor Championships: 1923, 1926, 1932, 1941, 1946\n*Won mixed doubles title at the U.S. Indoor Championships: 1923, 1924, 1926\u20131928\n*Won doubles title at the U.S. Grass Court Championships (for age 40 and over): 1940\u20131942, 1944, 1946\u20131950, 1952, 1954\n*U.S. Wightman Cup team member: 1923, 1924, 1927, 1929, 1931\n*U.S. Wightman Cup team captain: 1923, 1924, 1927, 1929, 1931, 1933, 1935, 1937\u20131939, 1946\u20131948\n*Winner of USTA Service Bowl, donated in Wightman's honor: 1940, 1946\n*Author of ''Better Tennis''\n*Coached several women champions, including [[Sarah Palfrey Cooke]], [[Helen Wills Moody]], and [[Helen Jacobs]]\n*Inducted into the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame]] in 1957\n*Appointed as an Honorary [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] in 1973\n*Inducted into the [[International Women's Sports Hall of Fame]] in 1986\n*First honoree in the University of California women's athlete hall of fame\n\n==Career in depth==\n[[File:Hazel Hotchkiss cropped.jpg|thumb]]\nThough short in stature, Wightman anticipated and moved extremely well around a tennis court. She perfected her volleying style early, hitting the ball against the family home in Berkeley, California, where she grew up and graduated from the University of California. She refused to let the ball bounce because the yard was so uneven. She used to play against her four brothers and then the proud and spiky Sutton sisters.\n\nWightman was a shy, somewhat awed, and fascinated 22-year-old college girl when she arrived at the Philadelphia Cricket Club in 1909 for the [[U.S. Open (tennis)|U.S. Championships]]. She never before played on grass, but she used her attacking style and rock-ribbed volleying\u2014she was the first woman to rely so heavily on the volley\u2014to win the all-comers final over [[Louise Hammond Raymond|Louise Hammond]] 6\u20138, 6\u20131, 6\u20134 and then the title over 39-year-old [[Maud Barger-Wallach]] 6\u20130, 6\u20131. Wightman also won the women's doubles and mixed doubles titles that year.\n\nIn the 1910 Washington State Championships, Wightman won one of the few recorded \"Golden Matches\" in which the winner did not lose a point. She defeated a Miss Huiskamp (first name unknown).<ref>''All-Time Records'', [[Tennis (magazine)|Tennis Magazine]], February 1981, page 72</ref>\n\nWightman successfully defended all three titles at the U.S. Championships in 1910 and 1911. Wightman easily defeated Hammond in the 1910 singles final. [[May Sutton]], an old West Coast rival and singles titlist at the U.S. Championships in 1904, pushed Wightman hard in the 1911 singles final before Wightman prevailed 8\u201310, 6\u20134, 9\u20137.\n\nThe most remarkable comeback in Wightman's career came at the singles final of the 1911 [[Niagara International Tennis Tournament]] against Sutton. After losing the first set 0\u20136 and going down 1\u20135 in the second, she won 12 straight games and the title 0\u20136, 7\u20135, 6\u20130.<ref name=ohnsorg/>\n\nIn 1912, Wightman married Bostonian George Wightman and did not defend her U.S. titles. However, responding to a challenge from her father to win after becoming a mother, which would be a U.S. first, she played again in 1915, losing the singles final to [[Molla Bjurstedt Mallory]] but winning the women's doubles and mixed doubles titles. At age 32, she won her fourth singles title with the loss of only one set, beating [[Marion Zinderstein]] 6\u20131, 6\u20132 in the final. She also reached the women's doubles final. Thereafter, her success (U.S. adult titles between 1909 and 1943) was limited to doubles.<ref name=ohnsorg/>\n\nWightman envisioned a team tournament for women similar to the [[Davis Cup]] and offered a silver vase as prize. In 1923, the British and Americans had the strongest women players. So, [[Julian Myrick]] of the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]] decided that a U.S.-Britain competition would be in order for the [[Wightman Cup]]. The event, with Wightman captaining and playing for a winning U.S. side, opened the newly constructed stadium at Forest Hills, New York. A treasured series, it lasted through 1989, disbanding when the event was no longer competitive.\n\nWightman, devoted to the game in all aspects, generously instructed innumerable players at no charge throughout her life. She also teamed with two of her prot\u00e9g\u00e9es who later joined her in the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame]] to win important titles: [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], U.S., and Olympic doubles titles with [[Helen Wills Moody]] in 1924 and U.S. Indoor women's doubles titles with [[Sarah Palfrey Cooke]] from 1928 through 1931. Her second Olympic gold medal in 1924 came in mixed doubles with [[R. Norris Williams|Dick Williams]].\n\nThe last of Wightman's record 34 U.S. adult titles was recorded in 1943 as she, 56, and [[Pauline Betz Addie]] won the women's doubles title at the [[US Indoors|U.S. Indoor Championships]] over [[Lillian Lopaus]] and [[Judy Atterbury]], 7\u20135, 6\u20131.\n\nWightman was included in the year-end top 10 rankings issued by the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]] in 1915, 1918, and 1919 and was the top ranked U.S. player in 1919 (rankings began in 1913).<ref>{{cite book |author=United States Tennis Association |title=1988 Official USTA Tennis Yearbook |publisher=H.O. Zimman, Inc |location=Lynn, Massachusetts |year=1988 |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |accessdate= |page=260}}</ref>\n\n== Grand Slam finals ==\n\n=== Singles: 5 ( 4 titles, 1 runner-up) ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:65px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:190px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:160px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n!style=\"width:15px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Ref.\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1909 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1909]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Maud Barger-Wallach]] || 6\u20130, 6\u20131 ||<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/wschamps.html|title = US Open Past Champions / Women's Singles|accessdate = 2015-10-09|website = US Open official website|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151006054223/http://www.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/wschamps.html|archivedate = 2015-10-06}}</ref>\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1910 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1910]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Louise Hammond Raymond]] || 6\u20134, 6\u20132 ||<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1911 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1911]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Florence Sutton]] || 8\u201310, 6\u20131, 9\u20137 ||\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up || [[1915 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1915]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Molla Mallory|Molla Bjurstedt]] || 6\u20134, 2\u20136, 0\u20136 ||<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1919 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1919]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Marion Zinderstein]] || 6\u20131, 6\u20132 ||<ref name=\":0\" />\n|}\n\n=== Doubles: 9 ( 7 titles, 2 runners-up) ===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:65px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:190px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:190px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:160px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n!style=\"width:15px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Ref.\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1909 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1909]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Edith Rotch]] || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dorothy Green (tennis)|Dorothy Green]]<br>{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Lois Moyes Bickle|Lois Moyes]] || 6\u20131, 6\u20131 ||<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/wdchamps.html|title = US Open Past Champions / Women's Doubles|accessdate = 2015-10-09|website = US Open official website|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151219121544/http://www.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/wdchamps.html|archivedate = 2015-12-19}}</ref>\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1910 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1910]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Edith Rotch]] || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Adelaide Browning]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Edna Wildey]] || 6\u20134, 6\u20134 ||<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1911 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1911]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Eleonora Sears]] || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dorothy Green (tennis)|Dorothy Green]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Florence Sutton]] || 6\u20134, 4\u20136, 6\u20132 ||<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1915 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1915]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass ||  {{flagicon|USA}} [[Eleonora Sears]] || {{flagicon|USA}} [[G. L. Chapman]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Helen Homans|Helen Homans McLean]] || 10\u20138, 6\u20132 ||<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up || [[1919 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1919]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass ||  {{flagicon|USA}} [[Eleonora Sears]] || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Eleanor Goss]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marion Zinderstein]] || 8\u201310, 7\u20139 ||<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up || [[1923 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1923]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass ||  {{flagicon|USA}} [[Eleanor Goss]] || {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Phyllis Covell|Phyllis Howkins Covell]]<br>{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Kathleen McKane Godfree|Kitty McKane]] || 6\u20132, 2\u20136, 1\u20136 ||<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-bgcolor= #cfc\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1924 Wimbledon Championships|1924]] || [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] || Grass ||  {{flagicon|USA}} [[Helen Wills]] || {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Phyllis Covell|Phyllis Howkins Covell]]<br>{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Kathleen McKane Godfree|Kitty McKane]] || 6\u20134, 6\u20134 ||<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/roll_of_honour/ladiesdoubles.html|title = Wimbledon Rolls of Honour / Ladies Doubles|date = |accessdate = 2015-10-09|website = Wimbledon official tournament website|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner || [[1924 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|1924]] || [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] || Grass ||  {{flagicon|USA}} [[Helen Wills]] || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Eleanor Goss]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marion Zinderstein|Marion Zinderstein Jessup]] || 6\u20134, 6\u20133 ||<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| 