-tar-heel-linked-to-bladens-second-positive-case|title=Coronavirus: Smithfield Foods worker at Tar Heel plant tests positive; a second Bladen resident also infected| date=April 18, 2020 |first1=Alan|last1=Wooten|work=[[The Bladen Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Bladen County, North Carolina]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.bladeninfo.org}}\n* [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=gyhANspY9yIC ''Bladen Journal,''] Google news archive. <small>\u2014PDFs of 2,696 issues, dating from 1929 to 1985.</small>\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Bladen County, North Carolina\n|North     = [[Cumberland County, North Carolina|Cumberland County]]\n|Northeast = [[Sampson County, North Carolina|Sampson County]]\n|East      =\n|Southeast = [[Pender County, North Carolina|Pender County]]\n|South     = [[Columbus County, North Carolina|Columbus County]]\n|Southwest =\n|West      = [[Robeson County, North Carolina|Robeson County]]\n|Northwest =\n}}\n\n{{Bladen County, North Carolina}}\n{{North_Carolina}}\n{{coord|34.62|-78.56|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-NC_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bladen County, North Carolina| ]]\n[[Category:1739 establishments in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1739]]\n", "name_user": "AgentNed", "label": "safe", "comment": "In the section of the article Other notableinformationi added the fact that theSmithfield Foodsprocessingplant inTar Heel, North Carolinareported a case ofCOVID-19on April 18th 2020.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bladen_County,_North_Carolina"}
{"title_page": "Fred Stolle", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian tennis player}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                  = Fred Stolle<br><small>[[Order of Australia|AO]]</small>\n|fullname              = Frederick Sydney Stolle\n|image                 =\n|country               = {{AUS}}\n|residence             = [[Aventura, Florida]], USA\n|birth_date            = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1938|10|8}}\n|birth_place           = [[Hornsby, New South Wales]], Australia\n|height                = {{height|ft=6|in=3}}<ref name=atpworldtour>{{cite web|title=Fred Stolle|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/en/players/enwiki/S129/overview|website=atpworldtour.com|publisher=[[Association of Tennis Professionals]]|accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n|turnedpro             = 1966<small> (amateur tour from 1958)\n|retired               = 1976\n|plays                 = Right-handed (one-handed backhand)\n|careerprizemoney      =\n|tennishofyear         = 1985\n|tennishofid           = fred-stolle\n|singlesrecord         = 815-408 (66.6%) <ref>{{cite web|title=Fred Stolle: Career match record|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player1=STOLLE,%20FRED&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n|singlestitles         = 39 <ref>{{cite web|title=Fred Stolle: Career match record|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player1=STOLLE,%20FRED&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=Tennis Base|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref>\n|highestsinglesranking= No. 2 (1966<small>, [[Lance Tingay]]</small>)<ref name=\"SydneyMorningHerald1966\">{{cite news|title=Stolle ranked second|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ggxiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=q-YDAAAAIBAJ&dq=stolle%20ranked%20second&pg=2601%2C1544591|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=5 October 1966|page=25|via=[[Google News Archive]]}}</ref>\n|AustralianOpenresult= F ([[1964 Australian Championships - Men's Singles|1964]], [[1965 Australian Championships - Men's Singles|1965]])\n|FrenchOpenresult= '''W''' ([[1965 French Championships - Men's Singles|1965]])\n|Wimbledonresult= F ([[1963 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|1963]], [[1964 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|1964]], [[1965 Wimbledon Championships - Men's Singles|1965]])\n|USOpenresult= '''W''' ([[1966 U.S. National Championships - Men's Singles|1966]])\n| Promajors              = yes\n| USProresult            = SF ([[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships#1967|1967]])\n| WembleyProresult       = 1R ([[Wembley Championship#1967|1967]])\n| FrenchProresult        = SF ([[French Pro Championship#1967|1967]])\n| TOCresult              =\n| doublesrecord=\n| doublestitles=\n| highestdoublesranking= No. '''1''' (1964)\n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult   = '''W''' (1963, 1964, 1966)\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult       = '''W''' (1965, 1968)\n| WimbledonDoublesresult        = '''W''' (1962, 1964)\n| USOpenDoublesresult           = '''W''' (1965, 1966, 1969)\n| OthertournamentsDoubles       = <!-- optional, adds a \"Major doubles tournaments\" title -->\n| MastersCupDoublesresult       = <!-- optional -->\n| Mixed                         = yes\n| mixedtitles                   =\n| mixedrecord                   =\n| AustralianOpenMixedresult     = '''W''' (1962, 1969)\n| FrenchOpenMixedresult         = F (1962, 1963, 1964)\n| WimbledonMixedresult          = '''W''' (1961, 1964, 1969)\n| USOpenMixedresult             = '''W''' (1962, 1965)\n}}\n\n'''Frederick Sydney Stolle''', [[Order of Australia|AO]]<ref name=\"ao\">{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1057578&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=STOLLE, Frederick Sydney, AO|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=23 December 2013}}</ref> (born 8 October 1938) is an Australian former [[tennis]] player and commentator. He was born in [[Hornsby, New South Wales]], Australia. He is the father of former Australian [[Davis Cup]] player [[Sandon Stolle]].\n\n==Career==\nStolle is notable for being the only male player in history to have lost his first five [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] singles finals, the fifth of which he led by two sets to love. However, Stolle went on to win two Grand Slam tournament singles titles, the [[1965 French Championships - Men's Singles|1965 French Championships]] and the [[1966 U.S. National Championships - Men's Singles|1966 US Championships]].<ref>{{cite magazine|author1=[[Frank Deford]]|title=A forgotten Aussie refreshes the memory|journal=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=19 September 1966|volume=25|issue=12|pages=105\u2013109|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1966/09/19/616920/a-forgotten-aussie-refreshes-the-memory}}</ref> At Wimbledon and the Australian Championships he finished as runner-up in these tournaments and losing to compatriot [[Roy Emerson]] on no fewer than five occasions. Lance Tingay of ''The Daily Telegraph'' ranked Stolle as World No. 2 in 1966.<ref name=\"SydneyMorningHerald1966\"/>\n\nStolle won ten Grand Slam doubles titles, partnering with compatriots [[Bob Hewitt]] (4 titles), Roy Emerson (4 titles) and [[Ken Rosewall]] (2 titles). In addition Stolle won 7 Grand Slam mixed doubles titles.\n\nAs a member of the Australian [[Davis Cup]] team Stolle won the Davis Cup title in 1964,<ref>{{cite magazine|author1=[[Frank Deford]]|title=Failure of a Winning Formula|journal=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=5 October 1964|volume=21|issue=14|pages=30\u201331|url=https://www.si.com/vault/issue/43198/44/2}}</ref> 1965 and 1966.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=\u00a1Ol\u00e9! Manolo\u2014a little bit too late|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1966/01/10/619110/ol-manoloa-little-bit-too-late|magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=Ernest Shirley|date=10 January 1966|volume=24|issue=2|pages=48\u201349}}</ref> In 1964 Stolle and Emerson were briefly suspended from the Australian Davis Cup team for going on an overseas tour in defiance of a Lawn Tennis Association of Australia order to remain in Australia until April.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The Outcasts Are Counted In|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1964/07/13/608312/the-outcasts-are-counted-in|magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]|author=John Lovesey|date=13 July 1964|volume=21|issue=2|pages=22,25}}</ref>\n\nStolle turned professional in 1966,<ref name=atpworldtour/> and as a pro, won two singles and 13 doubles titles. He earned about US$500,000 in career prize money.<ref>{{cite web|title=ATP Player Profile|url=http://www.atpworldtour.com/Tennis/Players/St/F/Fred-S-Stolle.aspx|publisher=[[Association of Tennis Professionals]] (ATP)|accessdate=30 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nStolle coached [[Vitas Gerulaitis]] from 1977 until 1983.\n\nFor many years, Stolle did TV commentary for ESPN and other tennis broadcasts. He currently provides commentary on [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tennis tournaments for Australia's [[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] and the [[Nine Network]].\n\n==Honours==\nFor his contribution to the tennis sport Fred Stolle was inducted into the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tennis Hall of Fame&nbsp;\u2013 Fred Stolle|url=http://www.tennisfame.com/hall-of-famers/fred-stolle|publisher=Newport International Tennis Hall of Fame|accessdate=30 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322151940/http://www.tennisfame.com/hall-of-famers/fred-stolle|archivedate=22 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1988 he was inducted into the [[Sport Australia Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sahof.org.au/hall-of-fame/member-profile/?memberID=443&memberType=athlete|title=Fred Stolle AO|publisher=Sport Australia Hall of Fame|accessdate=23 December 2013}}</ref> He received an [[Australian Sports Medal]] in 2000 and was made an Officer of the [[Order of Australia]] in 2005.<ref name=\"ao\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=982702&search_type=quick&showInd=true|title=Staale, Fred: Australian Sports Medal|publisher=It's an Honour|accessdate=24 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Grand Slam finals==\n\n===Singles (2 titles, 6 runners-up)===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:170px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:160px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#cfc;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss ||1963 || [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] ||Grass || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Chuck McKinley]]|| 7\u20139, 1\u20136, 4\u20136\n|-style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss ||1964 || [[Australian Open|Australian Championships]] ||Grass|| {{flagicon|Australia}} [[Roy Emerson]] || 3\u20136, 4\u20136, 2\u20136\n|-style=\"background:#cfc;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss ||1964 || Wimbledon ||Grass || {{flagicon|Australia}} Roy Emerson || 1\u20136, 10\u201312, 6\u20134, 3\u20136\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss ||1964 || [[U.S. Open (tennis)|US Championships]] ||Grass || {{flagicon|Australia}} Roy Emerson||4\u20136, 2\u20136, 4\u20136\n|-style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss ||1965 || Australian Championships||Grass || {{flagicon|Australia}} Roy Emerson || 9\u20137, 6\u20132, 4\u20136, 5\u20137, 1\u20136\n|-style=\"background:#ebc2af;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win ||1965||[[French Open|French Championships]]||Clay||{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Tony Roche]]||3\u20136, 6\u20130, 6\u20132, 6\u20133\n|-style=\"background:#cfc;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss ||1965 || Wimbledon ||Grass || {{flagicon|Australia}} Roy Emerson || 2\u20136, 4\u20136, 4\u20136\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win ||1966||US Championships||Grass ||{{flagicon|Australia}} [[John Newcombe]]||4\u20136, 12\u201310, 6\u20133, 6\u20134\n|}\n\n===Men'